&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I heard about the following today; An experimenter records at the &lt;br&gt;
&gt; same&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; time every day Mon-Fri. We hear about the importance of &lt;br&gt;
&gt; meditating,&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; automatic writing, etc at the same time every day but what we &lt;br&gt;
&gt; have to&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; remember with this, is that now we are in essence tuning into the &lt;br&gt;
&gt; same&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; radio show every day. One of my first experiments with the 469 &lt;br&gt;
&gt; had me&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; hearing this deep male voice over and over again. What was he &lt;br&gt;
&gt; trying&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; to tell me, I wondered. Than I realized that he was speaking&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; approximately every 18 seconds; every time the scan hit that &lt;br&gt;
&gt; station.&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; So, if you are removing up to 18 seconds between words, then you &lt;br&gt;
&gt; are&lt;br&gt;
